File:Â London's stock market opened lower on Monday, with the pound higher awaiting confirmation that the European Union would allow a Brexit extension until the end of January. LONDON - London's stock market opened lower on Monday, with the pound higher awaiting confirmation that the European Union would allow a Brexit extension until the end of January. The benchmark FTSE 100 index fell 0.2 percent to 7,312.03 points compared with Friday's close, as the pound edged up versus the dollar and euro. A stronger pound tends to weigh on the FTSE 100, which is composed of numerous multinationals earning in dollars. READ: Brexit on 31 October a priority, says Queen Elizabeth In the eurozone meanwhile, Frankfurt's DAX 30 index started the week with a gain of 0.1 percent to 12,906.08 points and the Paris CAC won 0.1 percent to 5,726.23. France was on Monday expected to join other EU members in granting a three-month extension to Britain's exit from the bloc, having initially expressed a desire for a shorter delay.